<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGGING A DITCH AT THE BORDER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Building a ditch to exclude "undesirables" is not a new idea. For example, the 
Romans often constructed an elaborate ditch and rampant (vallum) even going so 
far to ring a whole city (circumvallation) in order to starve its inhabitants. 
Hadrian's Wall, crossing Britain for 70 miles to connect the current sites of 
Carlisle and Newcastle-upon-Tyne, was intended to stop incursions by the Picts 
and the Scots. That wall was usually paralleled on its "friendly" side by a 
substantial vallum. 
</P>
<P>
Does that strategy work? I recently spent a year in Durham, 20 miles south of 
Hadrian's Wall. Never during that time was I molested by a marauding Pict. 
</P>
<P>
NATHANIEL GROSSMAN 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020489-0021 </DOCNO>
