<HEADLINE>
<P>
NAACP ASKS U.S. TO PROBE ALLEGED KKK INFLUENCE AT L.A. CENTRAL JAIL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN KENDALL, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The National Assn. for the Advancement of Colored People called Friday for a 
federal investigation into reports of racial tension at the Los Angeles County 
Central Jail, where two crosses allegedly were burned by white deputies in 
quarters housing black gang members. 
</P>
<P>
James Martin, director of the NAACP's western region, said his organization has 
been told by inmates and unnamed deputies that some of the white jailers belong 
to the Ku Klux Klan, the white supremacy organization that has made burning 
crosses a symbol of racial hatred. 
</P>
<P>
Beyond the allegation, Martin said there is no "solid evidence" any jail 
deputies are KKK members. Nonetheless, he told a press conference that the 
"NAACP is deeply concerned that KKK influence continues to exist in the Los 
Angeles County Jail. The Los Angeles NAACP . . . has contacted the (U.S.) 
attorney general with a request that they look into the situation." 
</P>
<P>
Sheriff's Capt. William Hinkle, commander of the 6,800-inmate jail, said 
Martin's statement is the first either he or members of his staff have heard of 
the KKK allegations, and he expressed doubt. 
</P>
<P>
"I spend a lot of time in the jail talking to inmates," Hinkle said. "To have 
that going on without coming to the surface is kind of hard to believe." 
</P>
<P>
The NAACP began to investigate jail conditions in December after receiving 
several letters, including one signed by 22 black gang members, complaining of 
misconduct and racial harassment, Martin said. 
</P>
<P>
The Sheriff's Department has begun an internal investigation into allegations 
of cross-burnings and other misconduct by deputies on the floors where gang 
members are kept. Four deputies and a sergeant were reassigned out of the jail 
this week after being accused of using "excessive force." The FBI this week 
began a separate investigation into the cross-burning allegations, which first 
surfaced in sworn testimony at an unrelated Civil Service hearing last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
