<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Federal Trade Commission, clearing the way for the nation's biggest merger, 
agreed not to challenge the $24.5-billion acquisition of RJR Nabisco by 
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. -- provided that the two companies sell 
certain products to reduce their market shares in ketchup, Oriental foods and 
packaged nuts. The commission, ruling on a preliminary agreement announced 
earlier this week, said KKR must within a year sell the Chun King Oriental 
foods line of RJR Nabisco or the La Choy line of Beatrice/Hunt-Wesson Inc., a 
unit of KKR; the Planters nuts line of RJR Nabisco or Beatrice's Fisher nuts 
line, and RJR Nabisco's Del Monte ketchup or Beatrice's Hunt's ketchup. An FTC 
official said that, if the brands were combined, they would have "probably 
slightly under 60%" of total sales of $300 million in Oriental foods; about 25% 
of the $500 million ketchup market, and about 50% of $1.5 billion in sales of 
packaged nuts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
