<HEADLINE>
<P>
FAMILY LIFE: ADOPTEES HELP EACH OTHER OUT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAN HOFMANN, Jan Hofmann is a regular contributor to Orange County Life. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Half a dozen strangers sat nervously in a circle of chairs Wednesday as the 
support group meeting got under way. 
</P>
<P>
"Let's go around the room and introduce ourselves," said Charice Leabo, the 
group leader, nodding toward the young woman on her left. 
</P>
<P>
"My name is Alison," she began, "And I'm an adoptee." 
</P>
<P>
Then she laughed. "This is weird. I feel like I'm at an AA meeting or 
something." Everyone else laughed too, and the ice was instantly broken. 
</P>
<P>
The group was Adoptee Awareness, a support organization started by Leabo, 19, 
of Tustin, an adoptee whose birth mother contacted her in August, 1988. 
Wednesday's meeting was the group's first. 
</P>
<P>
"I just wanted to be able to sit down and talk to someone who says, 'I 
understand,' and you know they really do understand," Leabo said. "My best 
friend is a good listener and I talk to her a lot, but she's not adopted and 
she can't really know what it's like." 
</P>
<P>
Leabo was "found," in the parlance of adoption, while some in the group are 
"searching." They don't know who their birth parents are, but they are trying 
to find out. Others aren't sure they want to know. As one young man put it, 
"I'm just lost." 
</P>
<P>
"I was adopted at 3 months," Leabo said. "A lot of times I felt I wasn't part 
of the family. I knew that I wasn't blood, that I didn't look like anybody. It 
was difficult for me to accept who I was. 
</P>
<P>
"I was angry at the world, and angry at my birth mother. Then I realized she 
was really unselfish. She was unmarried, by herself, didn't have any money. If 
she had kept me, she wouldn't have been able to take care of me." 
</P>
<P>
After she got over the anger, Leabo says, she didn't search because "I was so 
scared of hurting my adoptive mom. My (adoptive) father died when I was 13, and 
after that it was just the two of us. Then 6 years to the day after my father 
died, my phone rang, and it was Ilene (Wood). I got so excited I couldn't 
breathe. 
</P>
<P>
"The minute I saw her I felt so complete. I saw where I came from. It was like 
looking in the mirror." Leabo now lives with Wood, and she says her adoptive 
mother, who has moved to Missouri, accepts the situation and no longer feels 
threatened. 
</P>
<P>
Alison Hicks, 24, of Anaheim only recently began her search. "All my life I 
knew I was an adoptee. But I was curious; I wanted to know what my mother looks 
like," she said. "My parents have always been very supportive, but they said, 
'If you're going to do it, we'd rather you wait until you're out on your own. 
So I decided about 2 months ago that I would start." 
</P>
<P>
"I'm not looking for a new family," she said. "I'm just curious." On the advice 
of a search consultant from Concerned United Birthparents (CUB), a separate 
support group, Hicks filed papers requesting information from the Orange County 
adoption agency that placed her. She has an appointment next week to meet with 
an agency worker and get whatever information is available. 
</P>
<P>
"I felt like the first part of my life was never explained to me," said Chuck 
Whitmore, 21, of Temple City, who spent more than 3 years searching for his 
birth parents. 
</P>
<P>
"I went to the hospital where I was born, to the agency in L.A. that placed me. 
I even went to the closest church to the hospital and looked through their 
baptismal records. I got so depressed when I could find nothing at all. 
</P>
<P>
"I just wanted to know what they looked like. I wasn't sure I wanted to know 
more. I remember when I was 16 and I realized that my girlfriend looked like 
her brother and her dad. I thought that was neat, and I wondered if there was 
somebody out there I looked like." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
That's a common feeling among adoptees. "You see people who do look like you," 
Leabo said. "I remember before Ilene found me, wherever I went, to the beach, 
to Disneyland, to a restaurant, I would see people and wonder, 'Could that be 
them?' " 
</P>
<P>
Eventually, Whitmore learned from the agency that his mother had given him up 
because "she thought it was more important for me to have a two-parent home." 
After that, he said, "I went from just wanting to see a picture to wanting to 
meet this lady. 
</P>
<P>
"She loved me enough to give me up. That's a very strong love, I think. And 
it's kind of sad that we had to be apart. I'm glad I found her," he said. His 
birth mother, who lives in Orange County, still has not told her own parents 
about her unwed pregnancy, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Whitmore's 19-year-old brother, Randy, also adopted, says he isn't sure how 
much he wants to know about his own birth parents. He didn't even know about 
Chuck's search until the rest of the family was told, 9 months after Chuck and 
his birth mother first met in 1987 at a hotel near Disneyland. 
</P>
<P>
"I've got the greatest parents," Chuck said. "I didn't want them to feel I was 
leaving them." 
</P>
<P>
With the help of CUB, Chuck found his birth mother 19 months ago. "I wrote a 
letter to her, and then we got together. We see each other pretty often now. 
She came to one of my (motorcycle) races 2 weeks ago, and she got to see more 
of my real personality -- you know, how I act with my friends, instead of just 
some guy sitting around with his mother." 
</P>
<P>
His adoptive parents also met her at their request, and Chuck says that went 
well, although they don't have regular contact. 
</P>
<P>
Chuck said he and his birth mother "get along pretty good. There are a lot of 
similarities between us. We both drive fast; she drives faster than I do. I 
keep my room neat, and her house is absolutely spotless. We're like each other 
a lot." 
</P>
<P>
Chuck also got his birth father's name, address and phone number. He wrote a 
letter last year but got no response. "I'd like to meet him," he said. "But I 
don't want to push." 
</P>
<P>
"Being adopted has not made me a happy person," said Dave Ehlen, 26, of 
Anaheim. "I mean, I have a good family, but there's something missing, and I'm 
going to find it." 
</P>
<P>
After a series of frustrating phone calls to the adoption agency in San 
Antonio, Tex., his birthplace, Ehlen bought a ticket and flew there to do his 
own research. "But I walked away empty-handed," he said. "They wouldn't tell me 
anything. 
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to hurt these people (his birth parents)," Ehlen said. "Suppose 
she got married and had other kids and never told anyone about me? I'm not 
going to go up to her and say, 'Ta-dah!' I'd just let it go if I knew darn well 
that she didn't want to see me. But I don't know that. It's so frustrating, 
especially when (adoption agency workers) are sitting there with the files 
right behind them. 
</P>
<P>
"This woman's got to be thinking about me," he said. 
</P>
<P>
"I've been wanting to look since I was in the sixth grade," said Nancy Saar, 
21, of La Canada. "But my (adoptive) mom's scared I won't want her anymore." 
Saar said she has a physical description of her birth parents and some 
information on their backgrounds. "I think I look like my mom," she said. "I'm 
the same height as my mother was, and we both have brown hair. She loves 
horses, and so do I. I think we are probably pretty alike, and I want to pursue 
it. 
</P>
<P>
"My mom could have had an abortion, and then I couldn't have been here at all. 
I'm glad she didn't. But I want to know why she gave me up." 
</P>
<P>
Saar wasn't sure where to begin her search, however, so she came to Adoptee 
Awareness not only to share feelings, but for practical advice. 
</P>
<P>
But not all adoptees want contact with their birth parents, Leabo pointed out. 
"I got a call from a birth mother who found her daughter 2 years ago, and she 
won't have anything to do with her. She asked me to send her daughter a flyer 
for this meeting, and I did. She called me, and she was so angry, she said, 'I 
just don't understand why she won't leave me alone.' 
</P>
<P>
"I told her that it was up to her, but if she ever wanted to talk about it -- 
or about anything -- she could call me. She said she'd keep my number. I guess 
that's a start." 
</P>
<P>
Adoptee Awareness meetings are scheduled to be held the first Wednesday of 
every month at 7 p.m., at St. Paul's Episcopal Church, 1221 Wass St., Tustin. 
For more information, call (714) 558-0667. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Charice Leabo, founder of Adoptee Awareness, with her birth mother Ilene 
Wood at the support group's meeting in Tustin. CHRISTINE WALTER / Los Angeles 
Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
