<HEADLINE>
<P>
BUYING FIREWOOD -- A CONSUMER GUIDE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Clipboard researched by Rick VanderKnyff / Los Angeles Times. Graphics by 
Doris Shields / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There are a number of Orange County businesses that sell firewood in quantity. 
For some, selling wood is the main order of business; for others, including 
some tree services, it is a sideline. Don Sayles, owner of one of the county's 
largest firewood sellers, Woodshed Firewood in Orange, has some tips for 
buyers: Make sure the wood is already seasoned, a process that takes months. 
Ask the seller exactly how much wood is in a cord; some businesses, Sayles 
said, sell less than the standard 128 cubic feet (a stack of wood 4 feet by 4 
feet by 8 feet). 
</P>
<P>
Softwoods, he said, light easier than hardwoods but do not burn as long; Sayles 
recommends getting a mixture, with softwoods for starting the fire and 
hardwoods for sustaining it. Below is a sampling of county firewood sellers and 
their prices for a cord of different types of wood. Prices shown do not include 
delivery unless otherwise noted, although all the businesses listed do offer 
delivery. Quantities less than a cord are available, although some sellers have 
a minimum amount for delivery. Because of fluctuations in supply, prices are 
subject to change. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
